Subject: [PATCH] ClangImporter: add libc++ CxxStdlib support hooks

Swift's `CxxStdlib` stdlib build on Linux is wired up for libstdc++.
With CLANG_DEFAULT_CXX_STDLIB=libc++ baked into the toolchain (required
to make `std::__1::basic_string` reachable from Swift's CxxStdlib
overlay), the build fails compiling CxxStdlib's `std.swift` with
"underlying Objective-C module 'CxxStdlib' not found", because:

  1. swift's ClangImporter constructs cc1 args via
     `clang::createInvocation`. The driver's libc++ include path
     injection (which on a normal `clang -stdlib=libc++` invocation
     adds `<clang-binary>/../include/c++/v1` via
     `Toolchain::AddClangCXXStdlibIncludeArgs`) does NOT take effect
     for swift's internal mode.

  2. As a result, libc++'s public headers (`<chrono>`, `<string>`,
     etc.) and libc++'s own `module.modulemap` (which defines
     `module std`, what swift's existing name-aliasing logic maps to
     `import CxxStdlib`) are unreachable.

The fix: inject the libc++ include path explicitly into the swift
ClangImporter's invocation arg list when running on Linux with
`LangOpts.CXXStdlib == Libcxx`. The path is derived from the swift
resource-dir's `clang` symlink, which in any in-tree build points at
the actual clang resource-dir (e.g. `<llvm-build>/lib/clang/<v>/`).
libc++ lives at `<llvm-build>/include/c++/v1/`, reachable as
`<swift-resource>/clang/../../../include/c++/v1`.

Android needs a related ClangImporter-side fix with NDK 30. libc++ marks
C compatibility headers such as `<wchar.h>` as textual modules, so
building or verifying `CxxStdlib.swiftinterface` can include libc++'s
`<wchar.h>` more than once and trip duplicate preferred-overload shims
for `wcschr`, `wcspbrk`, `wcsrchr`, `wcsstr`, and `wmemchr`. Android's
C++ stdlib is libc++, so the importer defines
`_LIBCPP_WCHAR_H_HAS_CONST_OVERLOADS=1` for Android targets to suppress
that redundant shim block.

This patch is a candidate for filing upstream.

Sentinel: NUCLEUS_SWIFT_SOURCE_LIBCXX_LINUX,
          NUCLEUS_SWIFT_SOURCE_ANDROID_LIBCXX_WCHAR

diff --git a/lib/ClangImporter/ClangImporter.cpp b/lib/ClangImporter/ClangImporter.cpp
index e864387d440..bd92f74b73c 100644
--- a/lib/ClangImporter/ClangImporter.cpp
+++ b/lib/ClangImporter/ClangImporter.cpp
@@ -761,6 +761,43 @@ void importer::getNormalInvocationArguments(
     }
   }
 
+  // NUCLEUS_SWIFT_SOURCE_LIBCXX_LINUX:
+  // On Linux with libc++ as the C++ stdlib, swift's clang importer
+  // constructs cc1 args via `clang::createInvocation`. The driver's
+  // libc++ include path injection (which on a normal `clang -stdlib=libc++`
+  // invocation finds `<clang-binary>/../include/c++/v1`) does not happen
+  // for the swift-internal mode, so libc++'s public headers (`<chrono>`,
+  // `<string>`, etc.) and its own `module std` modulemap are unreachable.
+  // The CxxStdlib stdlib build fails with "underlying Objective-C module
+  // 'CxxStdlib' not found".
+  //
+  // Inject the libc++ include path explicitly when CXXStdlib is libc++.
+  // We derive it from the swift resource-dir's `clang` symlink, which
+  // points at the actual clang resource-dir
+  // (e.g. <llvm-build>/lib/clang/<v>/). libc++ lives at
+  // <llvm-build>/include/c++/v1/, which is reachable as
+  // <swift-resource>/clang/../../../include/c++/v1.
+  if (triple.isOSLinux() &&
+      LangOpts.CXXStdlib == CXXStdlibKind::Libcxx) {
+    llvm::SmallString<128> libcxxIncludePath(
+        searchPathOpts.RuntimeResourcePath);
+    llvm::sys::path::append(libcxxIncludePath, "clang", "..", "..");
+    llvm::sys::path::append(libcxxIncludePath, "..", "include", "c++", "v1");
+    invocationArgStrs.push_back("-isystem");
+    invocationArgStrs.push_back(libcxxIncludePath.str().str());
+  }
+
+  // NUCLEUS_SWIFT_SOURCE_ANDROID_LIBCXX_WCHAR:
+  // NDK 30's libc++ module map marks C compatibility headers such as
+  // <wchar.h> as textual. While importing the Android libc++ std module,
+  // Clang can textually include libc++'s <wchar.h> more than once and hit
+  // duplicate definitions for its preferred-overload shims. Android uses
+  // libc++ as its C++ stdlib, so define the guard libc++ uses to skip that
+  // redundant shim block.
+  if (triple.isAndroid()) {
+    invocationArgStrs.push_back("-D_LIBCPP_WCHAR_H_HAS_CONST_OVERLOADS=1");
+  }
+
   const std::string &moduleCachePath = importerOpts.ModuleCachePath;
   const std::string &scannerCachePath = importerOpts.ClangScannerModuleCachePath;
   // If a scanner cache is specified, this must be a scanning action. Prefer this
